@HedgeQuartersHQ Google is a perfect example.  By end of '26:
- AI Capex $250bln cumulative since '23. Depreciation now ~35bln/yr.
- Total revenue up 130bln, ~50% AI driven, so 60bln lets say.
- Margin ~35%, so 20bln in incremental profit.

Profit not covering depreciation, let alone needed IRR.

@ryanconnor Its not the loss timeframe that is the issue, its the orders of magnitude.  Cloud during that time was a 10yr bet that ate up about 10% of their free cashflow.  One of many.

AI capex is taking up 100% of their free cashflow in 2026.  Hurdle much higher.

@VrntPerception Some perception of a backstop may be motivating these folks to engage in uneconomic expansion, but that is exactly the point.

On the economics of the business, its not making rational sense even with an extraordinary outcome.

@ryanconnor Its so existential to each they are collectively operating irrationally.

@pmthn Why do you say I'm ignoring it?  The revenue could be internal or external.  Sheesh.

Its also notable that the internal use cases for companies like meta are marginal, and nothing close to what's needed to cover the capex.

https://t.co/mehuJVPTf0

@pmthn You can choose to read it, up to you.

The AI capex spend is over and above the maintenance capex they would have spent otherwise, which would have been needed to maintain revenues.  As a result incremental AI capex is best benchmarked against incremental income.

